{"sn1.46":{"sn1.46:0.1":{"pli":"Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.46 ","eng":"Linked Discourses 1.46 ","html":"<article id='sn1.46'><header><ul><li class='division'>{}</li>"},"sn1.46:0.2":{"pli":"5. Ādittavagga ","eng":"5. On Fire ","html":"<li>{}</li></ul>"},"sn1.46:0.3":{"pli":"Accharāsutta ","eng":"Nymphs ","html":"<h1 class='sutta-title'>{}</h1></header>"},"sn1.46:1.1":{"pli":"“Accharāgaṇasaṅghuṭṭhaṃ, ","eng":"“It’s resounding with a group of nymphs, ","html":"<blockquote class='gatha'><p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"The nymphs (<i lang='pi' translate='no'>accharā</i>, “aquatics”, perhaps originally cloud-deities) were known from Vedic times as beautiful dancers and musicians often romantically entwined with the <i lang='pi' translate='no'>gandhabba</i>. "},"sn1.46:1.2":{"pli":"pisācagaṇasevitaṃ; ","eng":"but haunted by a gang of goblins! ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"As horrifying as nymphs are seductive, the flesh-eating <i lang='pi' translate='no'>pisāca</i> (Sanskrit <i lang='pi' translate='no'>piśāca</i>) arises in troops under cover of night and slips through the air wreaking havoc. "},"sn1.46:1.3":{"pli":"Vanantaṃ mohanaṃ nāma, ","eng":"This grove is called ‘Deluding’. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"Delusion contains both desire and aversion. "},"sn1.46:1.4":{"pli":"kathaṃ yātrā bhavissatī”ti. ","eng":"How will I keep going?” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.46:2.1":{"pli":"“Ujuko nāma so maggo, ","eng":"“That path is called ‘the direct way’, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"This Sutta contrasts the “direct” way with the “deluding” (<i lang='pi' translate='no'>mohana</i>) way. This recalls the notion that the teaching shows the way to those who are lost (<i lang='pi' translate='no'>mūḷhassa vā maggaṁ ācikkheyya</i>, <a href='index.html?q=sn7.1#9.3'>SN 7.1:9.3</a>). This echoes the common description of the Saṅgha as practicing the way that is “direct”, suggesting that they are proceeding directly along a known route (<a href='index.html?q=sn11.3#11.2'>SN 11.3:11.2</a>). "},"sn1.46:2.2":{"pli":"abhayā nāma sā disā; ","eng":"and it’s headed for the place called ‘fearless’. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.46:2.3":{"pli":"Ratho akūjano nāma, ","eng":"The chariot is called ‘unswerving’, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.46:2.4":{"pli":"dhammacakkehi saṃyuto. ","eng":"fitted with wheels of the teaching. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>","comm":"Normally <i lang='pi' translate='no'>dhammacakka</i>, the “wheel of the teaching”, is singular, this being a unique plural. The commentary explains as mental and physical energy. "},"sn1.46:3.1":{"pli":"Hirī tassa apālambo, ","eng":"Conscience is its bench-back, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.46:3.2":{"pli":"satyassa parivāraṇaṃ; ","eng":"mindfulness its upholstery. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.46:3.3":{"pli":"Dhammāhaṃ sārathiṃ brūmi, ","eng":"I say the teaching is the driver, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.46:3.4":{"pli":"sammādiṭṭhipurejavaṃ. ","eng":"with right view running out in front. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.46:4.1":{"pli":"Yassa etādisaṃ yānaṃ, ","eng":"Any woman or man ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.46:4.2":{"pli":"itthiyā purisassa vā; ","eng":"who has such a vehicle, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.46:4.3":{"pli":"Sa ve etena yānena, ","eng":"by means of this vehicle ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.46:4.4":{"pli":"nibbānasseva santike”ti. ","eng":"has drawn near to extinguishment.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p></blockquote></article>"}},"sn1.47":{"sn1.47:0.1":{"pli":"Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.47 ","eng":"Linked Discourses 1.47 ","html":"<article id='sn1.47'><header><ul><li class='division'>{}</li>"},"sn1.47:0.2":{"pli":"5. Ādittavagga ","eng":"5. On Fire ","html":"<li>{}</li></ul>"},"sn1.47:0.3":{"pli":"Vanaropasutta ","eng":"Planters ","html":"<h1 class='sutta-title'>{}</h1></header>"},"sn1.47:1.1":{"pli":"“Kesaṃ divā ca ratto ca, ","eng":"“Whose merit always grows ","html":"<blockquote class='gatha'><p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.47:1.2":{"pli":"sadā puññaṃ pavaḍḍhati; ","eng":"by day and by night? ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.47:1.3":{"pli":"Dhammaṭṭhā sīlasampannā, ","eng":"What people—firm in principle, <j>accomplished in conduct—","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.47:1.4":{"pli":"ke janā saggagāmino”ti. ","eng":"are going to heaven?” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.47:2.1":{"pli":"“Ārāmaropā vanaropā, ","eng":"“Planters of parks or groves, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"This verse is cited at <a href='index.html?q=kv7.5'>Kv 7.5</a> in discussing the controverted point of whether the merit of a gift keeps growing even after it is given. "},"sn1.47:2.2":{"pli":"ye janā setukārakā; ","eng":"those who build a bridge, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.47:2.3":{"pli":"Papañca udapānañca, ","eng":"a drinking place and well, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.47:2.4":{"pli":"ye dadanti upassayaṃ. ","eng":"and those who give monastic quarters. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.47:3.1":{"pli":"Tesaṃ divā ca ratto ca, ","eng":"Their merit always grows ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.47:3.2":{"pli":"sadā puññaṃ pavaḍḍhati; ","eng":"by day and by night. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.47:3.3":{"pli":"Dhammaṭṭhā sīlasampannā, ","eng":"Those people—firm in principle, <j>accomplished in conduct—","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.47:3.4":{"pli":"te janā saggagāmino”ti. ","eng":"are going to heaven.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p></blockquote></article>"}},"sn1.48":{"sn1.48:0.1":{"pli":"Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.48 ","eng":"Linked Discourses 1.48 ","html":"<article id='sn1.48'><header><ul><li class='division'>{}</li>"},"sn1.48:0.2":{"pli":"5. Ādittavagga ","eng":"5. On Fire ","html":"<li>{}</li></ul>"},"sn1.48:0.3":{"pli":"Jetavanasutta ","eng":"Jeta’s Grove ","html":"<h1 class='sutta-title'>{}</h1></header>"},"sn1.48:1.1":{"pli":"“Idañhi taṃ jetavanaṃ, ","eng":"“This is indeed that Jeta’s Grove, ","html":"<blockquote class='gatha'><p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"These verses are also found at <a href='index.html?q=sn2.20'>SN 2.20</a>, where they are attributed to Anāthapiṇḍika. "},"sn1.48:1.2":{"pli":"isisaṅghanisevitaṃ; ","eng":"frequented by the Saṅgha of seers, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.48:1.3":{"pli":"Āvutthaṃ dhammarājena, ","eng":"where the King of Dhamma stayed: ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.48:1.4":{"pli":"pītisañjananaṃ mama. ","eng":"it brings me joy! ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.48:2.1":{"pli":"Kammaṃ vijjā ca dhammo ca, ","eng":"Deeds, knowledge, and principle; ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.48:2.2":{"pli":"sīlaṃ jīvitamuttamaṃ; ","eng":"ethical conduct, an excellent livelihood; ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.48:2.3":{"pli":"Etena maccā sujjhanti, ","eng":"by these are mortals purified, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.48:2.4":{"pli":"na gottena dhanena vā. ","eng":"not by clan or wealth. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.48:3.1":{"pli":"Tasmā hi paṇḍito poso, ","eng":"That’s why an astute person, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.48:3.2":{"pli":"sampassaṃ atthamattano; ","eng":"seeing what’s good for themselves, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.48:3.3":{"pli":"Yoniso vicine dhammaṃ, ","eng":"would examine the teaching rationally, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.48:3.4":{"pli":"evaṃ tattha visujjhati. ","eng":"and thus be purified in it. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.48:4.1":{"pli":"Sāriputtova paññāya, ","eng":"Sāriputta is full of wisdom, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"Anāthapiṇḍika was especially devoted to Sāriputta (see <a href='index.html?q=mn143'>MN 143</a>). "},"sn1.48:4.2":{"pli":"sīlena upasamena ca; ","eng":"ethics, and peace. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.48:4.3":{"pli":"Yopi pāraṅgato bhikkhu, ","eng":"Even a mendicant who has crossed over ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.48:4.4":{"pli":"etāvaparamo siyā”ti. ","eng":"might at best equal him.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p></blockquote></article>"}},"sn1.49":{"sn1.49:0.1":{"pli":"Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.49 ","eng":"Linked Discourses 1.49 ","html":"<article id='sn1.49'><header><ul><li class='division'>{}</li>"},"sn1.49:0.2":{"pli":"5. Ādittavagga ","eng":"5. On Fire ","html":"<li>{}</li></ul>"},"sn1.49:0.3":{"pli":"Maccharisutta ","eng":"Stingy ","html":"<h1 class='sutta-title'>{}</h1></header>"},"sn1.49:1.1":{"pli":"“Yedha maccharino loke, ","eng":"“Those folk in the world who are stingy, ","html":"<blockquote class='gatha'><p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.49:1.2":{"pli":"kadariyā paribhāsakā; ","eng":"miserly and abusive, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.49:1.3":{"pli":"Aññesaṃ dadamānānaṃ, ","eng":"setting up obstacles ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.49:1.4":{"pli":"antarāyakarā narā. ","eng":"for others who give. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.49:2.1":{"pli":"Kīdiso tesaṃ vipāko, ","eng":"What kind of result do they reap? ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.49:2.2":{"pli":"samparāyo ca kīdiso; ","eng":"What kind of future life? ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.49:2.3":{"pli":"Bhagavantaṃ puṭṭhumāgamma, ","eng":"We’ve come to ask you, worthy sir: ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.49:2.4":{"pli":"kathaṃ jānemu taṃ mayan”ti. ","eng":"how are we to understand this?” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.49:3.1":{"pli":"“Yedha maccharino loke, ","eng":"“Those folk in the world who are stingy, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.49:3.2":{"pli":"kadariyā paribhāsakā; ","eng":"miserly and abusive, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.49:3.3":{"pli":"Aññesaṃ dadamānānaṃ, ","eng":"setting up obstacles ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.49:3.4":{"pli":"antarāyakarā narā. ","eng":"for others who give: ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.49:4.1":{"pli":"Nirayaṃ tiracchānayoniṃ, ","eng":"they’re reborn in hell, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.49:4.2":{"pli":"yamalokaṃ upapajjare; ","eng":"the animal realm, or Yama’s world. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"Yama’s world is ambiguous. In standard Buddhist cosmology his realm stands above the gods of the Thirty-Three (<a href='index.html?q=mn97#30.18'>MN 97:30.18</a>), but here we would normally find the ghost realm (<i lang='pi' translate='no'>pettivisaya</i>). His true role is as guardian to the paths or rivers that lead one from one life to another (<a href='index.html?q=sn1.33#10.3'>SN 1.33:10.3</a>, <a href='index.html?q=mn130#3.1'>MN 130:3.1</a>, <a href='index.html?q=dhp235'>Dhp 235</a>). He was the son of Vivasvant (the sun) and brother of Manu, and as the first person to die, Rig Veda 10.4 tells us that he discovered the paths to the lands of the dead that he now guards with his pair of hounds. Yama is a righteous god, but sinners see him as horrifying due to their own guilt (Brahma Purāṇa 106.46). "},"sn1.49:4.3":{"pli":"Sace enti manussattaṃ, ","eng":"If they return to the human state, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.49:4.4":{"pli":"dalidde jāyare kule. ","eng":"they’re born in a poor family, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.49:5.1":{"pli":"Coḷaṃ piṇḍo ratī khiḍḍā, ","eng":"where clothes, food, pleasure, and play ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.49:5.2":{"pli":"yattha kicchena labbhati; ","eng":"are hard to find. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.49:5.3":{"pli":"Parato āsīsare bālā, ","eng":"They don’t even get ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.49:5.4":{"pli":"tampi tesaṃ na labbhati; ","eng":"what they hope for from others. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.49:5.5":{"pli":"Diṭṭhe dhammesa vipāko, ","eng":"This is the result in the present life, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.49:5.6":{"pli":"samparāye ca duggatī”ti. ","eng":"and in the next, a bad destination.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.49:6.1":{"pli":"“Itihetaṃ vijānāma, ","eng":"“We understand what you’re saying, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"This idiom is also found in the Parābhavasutta (<a href='index.html?q=snp1.6'>Snp 1.6</a>). "},"sn1.49:6.2":{"pli":"aññaṃ pucchāma gotama; ","eng":"and ask another question, Gotama. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.49:6.3":{"pli":"Yedha laddhā manussattaṃ, ","eng":"What about those who’ve gained the human state, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.49:6.4":{"pli":"vadaññū vītamaccharā. ","eng":"who are bountiful and rid of stinginess, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.49:7.1":{"pli":"Buddhe pasannā dhamme ca, ","eng":"confident in the Buddha and the teaching, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.49:7.2":{"pli":"saṅghe ca tibbagāravā; ","eng":"with keen respect for the Saṅgha? ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.49:7.3":{"pli":"Kīdiso tesaṃ vipāko, ","eng":"What kind of result do they reap? ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.49:7.4":{"pli":"samparāyo ca kīdiso; ","eng":"What kind of future life? ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.49:7.5":{"pli":"Bhagavantaṃ puṭṭhumāgamma, ","eng":"We’ve come to ask you, worthy sir: ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.49:7.6":{"pli":"kathaṃ jānemu taṃ mayan”ti. ","eng":"how are we to understand this?” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.49:8.1":{"pli":"“Yedha laddhā manussattaṃ, ","eng":"“Those who’ve gained the human state ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.49:8.2":{"pli":"vadaññū vītamaccharā; ","eng":"who are bountiful and rid of stinginess, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.49:8.3":{"pli":"Buddhe pasannā dhamme ca, ","eng":"confident in the Buddha and the teaching, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.49:8.4":{"pli":"saṅghe ca tibbagāravā; ","eng":"with keen respect for the Saṅgha: ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.49:8.5":{"pli":"Ete saggā pakāsanti, ","eng":"they illuminate the heavens ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"Read <i lang='pi' translate='no'>ete sagge pakāsenti</i> with PTS and BJT. "},"sn1.49:8.6":{"pli":"yattha te upapajjare. ","eng":"wherever they’re reborn. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.49:9.1":{"pli":"Sace enti manussattaṃ, ","eng":"If they return to the human state, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.49:9.2":{"pli":"aḍḍhe ājāyare kule; ","eng":"they’re reborn in a rich family, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.49:9.3":{"pli":"Coḷaṃ piṇḍo ratī khiḍḍā, ","eng":"where clothes, food, pleasure, and play ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.49:9.4":{"pli":"yatthākicchena labbhati. ","eng":"are easy to find. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.49:10.1":{"pli":"Parasambhatesu bhogesu, ","eng":"They rejoice like those ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.49:10.2":{"pli":"vasavattīva modare; ","eng":"who control the possessions of others. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.49:10.3":{"pli":"Diṭṭhe dhammesa vipāko, ","eng":"This is the result in the present life, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.49:10.4":{"pli":"samparāye ca suggatī”ti. ","eng":"and in the next, a good destination.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p></blockquote></article>"}},"sn1.5":{"sn1.5:0.1":{"pli":"Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.5 ","eng":"Linked Discourses 1.5 ","html":"<article id='sn1.5'><header><ul><li class='division'>{}</li>"},"sn1.5:0.2":{"pli":"1. Naḷavagga ","eng":"1. A Reed ","html":"<li>{}</li></ul>"},"sn1.5:0.3":{"pli":"Katichindasutta ","eng":"Cut How Many? ","html":"<h1 class='sutta-title'>{}</h1></header>"},"sn1.5:1.1":{"pli":"Sāvatthinidānaṃ. ","eng":"At Sāvatthī. ","html":"<p>{}</p>","comm":"The redactors show their playful side here, placing this “riddle of fives” as the fifth sutta of the Saṁyutta. | The enigmatic repetition of “five” is reminiscent of Bṛhadāraṇyaka Upaniṣad 4.4.17: “Where the five groups of five and space are established, I regard that Self as the immortal Brahman, knowing which I am immortal.” Or perhaps it is a reference to the five great sacrifices, to sages, gods, ghosts, men and ancestors (Manu 4.21). "},"sn1.5:1.2":{"pli":"Ekamantaṃ ṭhitā kho sā devatā bhagavato santike imaṃ gāthaṃ abhāsi: ","eng":"Standing to one side, that deity spoke this verse in the Buddha’s presence: ","html":"<p>{}</p>"},"sn1.5:2.1":{"pli":"“Kati chinde kati jahe, ","eng":"“Cut how many? Drop how many? ","html":"<blockquote class='gatha'><p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.5:2.2":{"pli":"kati cuttari bhāvaye; ","eng":"Develop how many more? ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.5:2.3":{"pli":"Kati saṅgātigo bhikkhu, ","eng":"When a mendicant slips how many chains ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.5:2.4":{"pli":"oghatiṇṇoti vuccatī”ti. ","eng":"are they said to have crossed the flood?” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.5:3.1":{"pli":"“Pañca chinde pañca jahe, ","eng":"“Five to cut, five to drop, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"According to the commentary, the five lower fetters are cut, the five higher fetters are dropped, and the five faculties are developed. "},"sn1.5:3.2":{"pli":"pañca cuttari bhāvaye; ","eng":"and five more to develop. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.5:3.3":{"pli":"Pañca saṅgātigo bhikkhu, ","eng":"When a mendicant slips five chains ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"The “five chains” are not defined in the Suttas, but <a href='index.html?q=vb17#238.1'>Vb 17:238.1</a> identifies them as greed, hate, delusion, conceit, and views. "},"sn1.5:3.4":{"pli":"oghatiṇṇoti vuccatī”ti. ","eng":"they’re said to have crossed the flood.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p></blockquote></article>"}},"sn1.50":{"sn1.50:0.1":{"pli":"Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.50 ","eng":"Linked Discourses 1.50 ","html":"<article id='sn1.50'><header><ul><li class='division'>{}</li>"},"sn1.50:0.2":{"pli":"5. Ādittavagga ","eng":"5. On Fire ","html":"<li>{}</li></ul>"},"sn1.50:0.3":{"pli":"Ghaṭīkārasutta ","eng":"With Ghaṭīkāra ","html":"<h1 class='sutta-title'>{}</h1></header>"},"sn1.50:1.1":{"pli":"“Avihaṃ upapannāse, ","eng":"“Seven mendicants reborn in Aviha ","html":"<blockquote class='gatha'><p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"This discourse, with more background, is also at <a href='index.html?q=sn2.24'>SN 2.24</a>. | Aviha is one of the realms in which non-returners are born. The speaker is announcing that these seven have become perfected ones in that realm. "},"sn1.50:1.2":{"pli":"vimuttā satta bhikkhavo; ","eng":"have been freed. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.50:1.3":{"pli":"Rāgadosaparikkhīṇā, ","eng":"With the complete ending of greed and hate, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.50:1.4":{"pli":"tiṇṇā loke visattikan”ti. ","eng":"they’ve crossed over clinging to the world.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.50:2.1":{"pli":"“Ke ca te ataruṃ paṅkaṃ, ","eng":"“Who are those who’ve crossed the bog, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.50:2.2":{"pli":"maccudheyyaṃ suduttaraṃ; ","eng":"Death’s dominion so hard to pass? ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.50:2.3":{"pli":"Ke hitvā mānusaṃ dehaṃ, ","eng":"Who, after leaving behind the human body, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"I follow Bodhi in using the BJT readings, with variants in notes. "},"sn1.50:2.4":{"pli":"dibbayogaṃ upaccagun”ti. ","eng":"have risen above celestial yokes?” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.50:3.1":{"pli":"“Upako palagaṇḍo ca, ","eng":"“Upaka and Palagaṇḍa, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"An Ājīvaka ascetic named Upaka met the Buddha shortly after his awakening, but was unconvinced (<a href='index.html?q=mn26#25.1'>MN 26:25.1</a>); the commentary says that this was he. Another Upaka, a layman, encounters the Buddha at <a href='index.html?q=an4.188'>AN 4.188</a>. | Palagaṇḍa means “mason”, but no-one of that name is known. "},"sn1.50:3.2":{"pli":"pukkusāti ca te tayo; ","eng":"and Pukkusāti, these three; ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"The story of Pukkusāti is told in <a href='index.html?q=mn140'>MN 140</a>. "},"sn1.50:3.3":{"pli":"Bhaddiyo khaṇḍadevo ca, ","eng":"Bhaddiya and Bhaddadeva, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"Several mendicants named Bhaddiya are known, but they are arahants so it does not fit. A Licchavī layman of the same name appears in <a href='index.html?q=an4.193'>AN 4.193</a>, but there is no indication he went forth. | Bhaddadeva (<i lang='pi' translate='no'>khaṇḍadeva</i>) is otherwise unknown. "},"sn1.50:3.4":{"pli":"bāhuraggi ca siṅgiyo; ","eng":"and Bāhudanti and Piṅgiya. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"Bāhudanti (<i lang='pi' translate='no'>bāhuraggi</i>, <i lang='pi' translate='no'>bahunandi</i>) is also a name of Indra, the “son of Bahudantī”. | Piṅgiya (<i lang='pi' translate='no'>siṅgiya</i>) is probably the brahmin ascetic who features in <a href='index.html?q=snp5.17'>Snp 5.17</a>. "},"sn1.50:3.5":{"pli":"Te hitvā mānusaṃ dehaṃ, ","eng":"They, after leaving behind the human body, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.50:3.6":{"pli":"dibbayogaṃ upaccagun”ti. ","eng":"have risen above celestial yokes.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.50:4.1":{"pli":"“Kusalī bhāsasī tesaṃ, ","eng":"“You speak well of them, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.50:4.2":{"pli":"mārapāsappahāyinaṃ; ","eng":"who have let go the snares of Māra. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.50:4.3":{"pli":"Kassa te dhammamaññāya, ","eng":"Whose teaching did they understand ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.50:4.4":{"pli":"acchiduṃ bhavabandhanan”ti. ","eng":"to cut the bonds of rebirth?” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.50:5.1":{"pli":"“Na aññatra bhagavatā, ","eng":"“None other than the Blessed One! ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.50:5.2":{"pli":"nāññatra tava sāsanā; ","eng":"None other than your instruction! ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.50:5.3":{"pli":"Yassa te dhammamaññāya, ","eng":"It was your teaching that they understood ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.50:5.4":{"pli":"acchiduṃ bhavabandhanaṃ. ","eng":"to cut the bonds of rebirth. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.50:6.1":{"pli":"Yattha nāmañca rūpañca, ","eng":"Where name and form ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.50:6.2":{"pli":"asesaṃ uparujjhati; ","eng":"cease with nothing left over; ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.50:6.3":{"pli":"Taṃ te dhammaṃ idhaññāya, ","eng":"understanding this teaching, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.50:6.4":{"pli":"acchiduṃ bhavabandhanan”ti. ","eng":"they cut the bonds of rebirth.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.50:7.1":{"pli":"“Gambhīraṃ bhāsasī vācaṃ, ","eng":"“The words you say are deep, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.50:7.2":{"pli":"dubbijānaṃ sudubbudhaṃ; ","eng":"hard to understand, so very hard to wake up to. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.50:7.3":{"pli":"Kassa tvaṃ dhammamaññāya, ","eng":"Whose teaching did you understand ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.50:7.4":{"pli":"vācaṃ bhāsasi īdisan”ti. ","eng":"that you can say such things?” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.50:8.1":{"pli":"“Kumbhakāro pure āsiṃ, ","eng":"“In the past I was a potter ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"This story is told in detail in <a href='index.html?q=mn81'>MN 81</a>. "},"sn1.50:8.2":{"pli":"vekaḷiṅge ghaṭīkaro; ","eng":"in Vebhaliṅga called Ghaṭīkāra. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.50:8.3":{"pli":"Mātāpettibharo āsiṃ, ","eng":"I took care of my parents ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.50:8.4":{"pli":"kassapassa upāsako. ","eng":"as a lay follower of Buddha Kassapa. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.50:9.1":{"pli":"Virato methunā dhammā, ","eng":"I refrained from sexual intercourse, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.50:9.2":{"pli":"brahmacārī nirāmiso; ","eng":"I was chaste, spiritual. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.50:9.3":{"pli":"Ahuvā te sagāmeyyo, ","eng":"We lived in the same village; ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.50:9.4":{"pli":"ahuvā te pure sakhā. ","eng":"in the past I was your comrade. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.50:10.1":{"pli":"Sohamete pajānāmi, ","eng":"I am the one who understands ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.50:10.2":{"pli":"vimutte satta bhikkhavo; ","eng":"that these seven mendicants have been freed. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.50:10.3":{"pli":"Rāgadosaparikkhīṇe, ","eng":"With the complete ending of greed and hate, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.50:10.4":{"pli":"tiṇṇe loke visattikan”ti. ","eng":"they’ve crossed over clinging to the world.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.50:11.1":{"pli":"“Evametaṃ tadā āsi, ","eng":"“That’s exactly how it was, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.50:11.2":{"pli":"yathā bhāsasi bhaggava; ","eng":"just as you say, Bhaggava. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"The Buddha calls him by his clan name, as the Buddha Kassapa does at <a href='index.html?q=mn81#19.3'>MN 81:19.3</a>. "},"sn1.50:11.3":{"pli":"Kumbhakāro pure āsi, ","eng":"In the past you were a potter ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.50:11.4":{"pli":"vekaḷiṅge ghaṭīkaro; ","eng":"in Vebhaliṅga called Ghaṭīkāra. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.50:11.5":{"pli":"Mātāpettibharo āsi, ","eng":"You took care of your parents ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.50:11.6":{"pli":"kassapassa upāsako. ","eng":"as a lay follower of Buddha Kassapa. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.50:12.1":{"pli":"Virato methunā dhammā, ","eng":"You refrained from sexual intercourse, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.50:12.2":{"pli":"brahmacārī nirāmiso; ","eng":"you were chaste, spiritual. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.50:12.3":{"pli":"Ahuvā me sagāmeyyo, ","eng":"We lived in the same village; ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.50:12.4":{"pli":"ahuvā me pure sakhā”ti. ","eng":"in the past you were my comrade.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.50:13.1":{"pli":"“Evametaṃ purāṇānaṃ, ","eng":"That’s how it was ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"The commentary says that this verse was added by the redactors. "},"sn1.50:13.2":{"pli":"sahāyānaṃ ahu saṅgamo; ","eng":"when those friends of old met again. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.50:13.3":{"pli":"Ubhinnaṃ bhāvitattānaṃ, ","eng":"Both of them were evolved, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.50:13.4":{"pli":"sarīrantimadhārinan”ti. ","eng":"bearing their final body. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p></blockquote>","comm":"This confirms that Ghaṭīkāra, too, had realized arahantship in his final birth in Aviha. This explains how he was able to know that the others were arahants. "},"sn1.50:13.5":{"pli":"Ādittavaggo pañcamo. ","html":"<p class='endvagga'>{}</p>"},"sn1.50:14.0":{"pli":"Tassuddānaṃ ","html":"<p class='uddana-intro'>{}</p>"},"sn1.50:14.1":{"pli":"Ādittaṃ kiṃdadaṃ annaṃ, ","html":"<blockquote class='uddanagatha'><p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.50:14.2":{"pli":"ekamūlaanomiyaṃ; ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.50:14.3":{"pli":"Accharāvanaropajetaṃ, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.50:14.4":{"pli":"maccharena ghaṭīkaroti. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p></blockquote></article>"}},"sn1.51":{"sn1.51:0.1":{"pli":"Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.51 ","eng":"Linked Discourses 1.51 ","html":"<article id='sn1.51'><header><ul><li class='division'>{}</li>"},"sn1.51:0.2":{"pli":"6. Jarāvagga ","eng":"6. Old Age ","html":"<li>{}</li></ul>"},"sn1.51:0.3":{"pli":"Jarāsutta ","eng":"Old Age ","html":"<h1 class='sutta-title'>{}</h1></header>"},"sn1.51:1.1":{"pli":"“Kiṃsu yāva jarā sādhu, ","eng":"“What’s still good in old age? ","html":"<blockquote class='gatha'><p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.51:1.2":{"pli":"kiṃsu sādhu patiṭṭhitaṃ; ","eng":"What’s good when grounded? ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.51:1.3":{"pli":"Kiṃsu narānaṃ ratanaṃ, ","eng":"What is people’s treasure? ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.51:1.4":{"pli":"kiṃsu corehi dūharan”ti. ","eng":"What’s hard for thieves to take?” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.51:2.1":{"pli":"“Sīlaṃ yāva jarā sādhu, ","eng":"“Ethics are still good in old age. ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.51:2.2":{"pli":"saddhā sādhu patiṭṭhitā; ","eng":"Faith is good when grounded. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.51:2.3":{"pli":"Paññā narānaṃ ratanaṃ, ","eng":"Wisdom is people’s treasure. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.51:2.4":{"pli":"puññaṃ corehi dūharan”ti. ","eng":"Merit’s hard for thieves to take.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p></blockquote></article>"}},"sn1.52":{"sn1.52:0.1":{"pli":"Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.52 ","eng":"Linked Discourses 1.52 ","html":"<article id='sn1.52'><header><ul><li class='division'>{}</li>"},"sn1.52:0.2":{"pli":"6. Jarāvagga ","eng":"6. Old Age ","html":"<li>{}</li></ul>"},"sn1.52:0.3":{"pli":"Ajarasāsutta ","eng":"Getting Old ","html":"<h1 class='sutta-title'>{}</h1></header>"},"sn1.52:1.1":{"pli":"“Kiṃsu ajarasā sādhu, ","eng":"“What’s good because it never gets old? ","html":"<blockquote class='gatha'><p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.52:1.2":{"pli":"kiṃsu sādhu adhiṭṭhitaṃ; ","eng":"What’s good when committed? ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.52:1.3":{"pli":"Kiṃsu narānaṃ ratanaṃ, ","eng":"What is people’s treasure? ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.52:1.4":{"pli":"kiṃsu corehyahāriyan”ti. ","eng":"What can thieves never take?” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.52:2.1":{"pli":"“Sīlaṃ ajarasā sādhu, ","eng":"“Ethics are good because they never grow old. ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.52:2.2":{"pli":"saddhā sādhu adhiṭṭhitā; ","eng":"Faith is good when committed. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"The previous discourse had <i lang='pi' translate='no'>patiṭṭhitā</i> (“grounded”, i.e. based on reason), whereas here we have <i lang='pi' translate='no'>adhiṭṭhitā</i> (“committed”, i.e. unwavering). "},"sn1.52:2.3":{"pli":"Paññā narānaṃ ratanaṃ, ","eng":"Wisdom is people’s treasure. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.52:2.4":{"pli":"puññaṃ corehyahāriyan”ti. ","eng":"Merit’s what thieves can never take.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p></blockquote></article>"}},"sn1.53":{"sn1.53:0.1":{"pli":"Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.53 ","eng":"Linked Discourses 1.53 ","html":"<article id='sn1.53'><header><ul><li class='division'>{}</li>"},"sn1.53:0.2":{"pli":"6. Jarāvagga ","eng":"6. Old Age ","html":"<li>{}</li></ul>"},"sn1.53:0.3":{"pli":"Mittasutta ","eng":"A Friend ","html":"<h1 class='sutta-title'>{}</h1></header>"},"sn1.53:1.1":{"pli":"“Kiṃsu pavasato mittaṃ, ","eng":"“Who’s your friend while journeying? ","html":"<blockquote class='gatha'><p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.53:1.2":{"pli":"kiṃsu mittaṃ sake ghare; ","eng":"Who’s your friend at home? ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.53:1.3":{"pli":"Kiṃ mittaṃ atthajātassa, ","eng":"Who’s your friend in need? ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.53:1.4":{"pli":"kiṃ mittaṃ samparāyikan”ti. ","eng":"Who’s your friend in the next life?” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.53:2.1":{"pli":"“Sattho pavasato mittaṃ, ","eng":"“A caravan is your friend while journeying. ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.53:2.2":{"pli":"mātā mittaṃ sake ghare; ","eng":"Mother is your friend at home. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.53:2.3":{"pli":"Sahāyo atthajātassa, ","eng":"An ally in a time of need ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.53:2.4":{"pli":"hoti mittaṃ punappunaṃ; ","eng":"is a friend time and again. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.53:2.5":{"pli":"Sayaṅkatāni puññāni, ","eng":"But the good deeds you’ve done yourself—","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.53:2.6":{"pli":"taṃ mittaṃ samparāyikan”ti. ","eng":"that’s your friend in the next life.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p></blockquote></article>"}},"sn1.54":{"sn1.54:0.1":{"pli":"Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.54 ","eng":"Linked Discourses 1.54 ","html":"<article id='sn1.54'><header><ul><li class='division'>{}</li>"},"sn1.54:0.2":{"pli":"6. Jarāvagga ","eng":"6. Old Age ","html":"<li>{}</li></ul>"},"sn1.54:0.3":{"pli":"Vatthusutta ","eng":"Grounds ","html":"<h1 class='sutta-title'>{}</h1></header>"},"sn1.54:1.1":{"pli":"“Kiṃsu vatthu manussānaṃ, ","eng":"“What is the site for human beings? ","html":"<blockquote class='gatha'><p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.54:1.2":{"pli":"kiṃsūdha paramo sakhā; ","eng":"What is the best comrade here? ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.54:1.3":{"pli":"Kiṃsu bhūtā upajīvanti, ","eng":"By what do the creatures who live off the earth ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.54:1.4":{"pli":"ye pāṇā pathavissitā”ti. ","eng":"sustain their life?” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.54:2.1":{"pli":"“Puttā vatthu manussānaṃ, ","eng":"“Children are the site for human beings. ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.54:2.2":{"pli":"bhariyā ca paramo sakhā; ","eng":"A wife is the best comrade. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"See <a href='index.html?q=an7.63#10.1'>AN 7.63:10.1</a>. "},"sn1.54:2.3":{"pli":"Vuṭṭhiṃ bhūtā upajīvanti, ","eng":"The creatures who live off the earth ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.54:2.4":{"pli":"ye pāṇā pathavissitā”ti. ","eng":"sustain their life by rain.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p></blockquote></article>","comm":"For eulogies of rain, see the related verse at <a href='index.html?q=sn1.80#4.1'>SN 1.80:4.1</a>, and also <a href='index.html?q=sn1.13#3.4'>SN 1.13:3.4</a>, <a href='index.html?q=sn1.74#2.2'>SN 1.74:2.2</a>. "}},"sn1.55":{"sn1.55:0.1":{"pli":"Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.55 ","eng":"Linked Discourses 1.55 ","html":"<article id='sn1.55'><header><ul><li class='division'>{}</li>"},"sn1.55:0.2":{"pli":"6. Jarāvagga ","eng":"6. Old Age ","html":"<li>{}</li></ul>"},"sn1.55:0.3":{"pli":"Paṭhamajanasutta ","eng":"Gives Birth (1st) ","html":"<h1 class='sutta-title'>{}</h1></header>"},"sn1.55:1.1":{"pli":"“Kiṃsu janeti purisaṃ, ","eng":"“What gives birth to a person? ","html":"<blockquote class='gatha'><p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.55:1.2":{"pli":"kiṃsu tassa vidhāvati; ","eng":"What do they have that runs about? ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.55:1.3":{"pli":"Kiṃsu saṃsāramāpādi, ","eng":"What enters transmigration? ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.55:1.4":{"pli":"kiṃsu tassa mahabbhayan”ti. ","eng":"What’s their greatest fear?” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.55:2.1":{"pli":"“Taṇhā janeti purisaṃ, ","eng":"“Craving gives birth to a person. ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.55:2.2":{"pli":"cittamassa vidhāvati; ","eng":"Their mind is what runs about. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.55:2.3":{"pli":"Satto saṃsāramāpādi, ","eng":"A sentient being enters transmigration. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.55:2.4":{"pli":"dukkhamassa mahabbhayan”ti. ","eng":"Suffering is their greatest fear.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p></blockquote></article>"}},"sn1.56":{"sn1.56:0.1":{"pli":"Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.56 ","eng":"Linked Discourses 1.56 ","html":"<article id='sn1.56'><header><ul><li class='division'>{}</li>"},"sn1.56:0.2":{"pli":"6. Jarāvagga ","eng":"6. Old Age ","html":"<li>{}</li></ul>"},"sn1.56:0.3":{"pli":"Dutiyajanasutta ","eng":"Gives Birth (2nd) ","html":"<h1 class='sutta-title'>{}</h1></header>"},"sn1.56:1.1":{"pli":"“Kiṃsu janeti purisaṃ, ","eng":"“What gives birth to a person? ","html":"<blockquote class='gatha'><p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.56:1.2":{"pli":"kiṃsu tassa vidhāvati; ","eng":"What do they have that runs about? ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.56:1.3":{"pli":"Kiṃsu saṃsāramāpādi, ","eng":"What enters transmigration? ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.56:1.4":{"pli":"kismā na parimuccatī”ti. ","eng":"From what are they not free?” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.56:2.1":{"pli":"“Taṇhā janeti purisaṃ, ","eng":"“Craving gives birth to a person. ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.56:2.2":{"pli":"cittamassa vidhāvati; ","eng":"Their mind is what runs about. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.56:2.3":{"pli":"Satto saṃsāramāpādi, ","eng":"A sentient being enters transmigration. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.56:2.4":{"pli":"dukkhā na parimuccatī”ti. ","eng":"From suffering they are not free.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p></blockquote></article>"}},"sn1.57":{"sn1.57:0.1":{"pli":"Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.57 ","eng":"Linked Discourses 1.57 ","html":"<article id='sn1.57'><header><ul><li class='division'>{}</li>"},"sn1.57:0.2":{"pli":"6. Jarāvagga ","eng":"6. Old Age ","html":"<li>{}</li></ul>"},"sn1.57:0.3":{"pli":"Tatiyajanasutta ","eng":"Gives Birth (3rd) ","html":"<h1 class='sutta-title'>{}</h1></header>"},"sn1.57:1.1":{"pli":"“Kiṃsu janeti purisaṃ, ","eng":"“What gives birth to a person? ","html":"<blockquote class='gatha'><p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.57:1.2":{"pli":"kiṃsu tassa vidhāvati; ","eng":"What do they have that runs about? ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.57:1.3":{"pli":"Kiṃsu saṃsāramāpādi, ","eng":"What enters transmigration? ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.57:1.4":{"pli":"kiṃsu tassa parāyanan”ti. ","eng":"What is their destiny?” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.57:2.1":{"pli":"“Taṇhā janeti purisaṃ, ","eng":"“Craving gives birth to a person. ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.57:2.2":{"pli":"cittamassa vidhāvati; ","eng":"Their mind is what runs about. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.57:2.3":{"pli":"Satto saṃsāramāpādi, ","eng":"A sentient being enters transmigration. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.57:2.4":{"pli":"kammaṃ tassa parāyanan”ti. ","eng":"Deeds are their destiny.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p></blockquote></article>","comm":"This is illustrated at <a href='index.html?q=sn3.21'>SN 3.21</a>. "}},"sn1.58":{"sn1.58:0.1":{"pli":"Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.58 ","eng":"Linked Discourses 1.58 ","html":"<article id='sn1.58'><header><ul><li class='division'>{}</li>"},"sn1.58:0.2":{"pli":"6. Jarāvagga ","eng":"6. Old Age ","html":"<li>{}</li></ul>"},"sn1.58:0.3":{"pli":"Uppathasutta ","eng":"Deviation ","html":"<h1 class='sutta-title'>{}</h1></header>"},"sn1.58:1.1":{"pli":"“Kiṃsu uppatho akkhāto, ","eng":"“What’s declared to be a deviation? ","html":"<blockquote class='gatha'><p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"“Deviation” is <i lang='pi' translate='no'>uppatha</i> (“off course”). | These questions and answers are included in <a href='index.html?q=sn1.76'>SN 1.76</a>. "},"sn1.58:1.2":{"pli":"kiṃsu rattindivakkhayo; ","eng":"What is ending day and night? ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.58:1.3":{"pli":"Kiṃ malaṃ brahmacariyassa, ","eng":"What’s the stain of chastity? ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.58:1.4":{"pli":"kiṃ sinānamanodakan”ti. ","eng":"What’s the waterless bath?” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>","comm":"A reference to the belief that bathing in water brings purity. Compare the “inner bathing” at <a href='index.html?q=mn7#18.5'>MN 7:18.5</a>. "},"sn1.58:2.1":{"pli":"“Rāgo uppatho akkhāto, ","eng":"“Lust is declared to be a deviation. ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.58:2.2":{"pli":"Vayo rattindivakkhayo; ","eng":"Youth is ending day and night. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.58:2.3":{"pli":"Itthī malaṃ brahmacariyassa, ","eng":"Women are the stain of chastity, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.58:2.4":{"pli":"Etthāyaṃ sajjate pajā; ","eng":"to which this generation clings. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.58:2.5":{"pli":"Tapo ca brahmacariyañca, ","eng":"Fervor and chastity ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"“Fervor and celibacy” (<i lang='pi' translate='no'>tapas</i> and <i lang='pi' translate='no'>brahmacariya</i>) are closely linked in Atharvaveda 11.5. "},"sn1.58:2.6":{"pli":"Taṃ sinānamanodakan”ti. ","eng":"are the waterless bath.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p></blockquote></article>"}},"sn1.59":{"sn1.59:0.1":{"pli":"Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.59 ","eng":"Linked Discourses 1.59 ","html":"<article id='sn1.59'><header><ul><li class='division'>{}</li>"},"sn1.59:0.2":{"pli":"6. Jarāvagga ","eng":"6. Old Age ","html":"<li>{}</li></ul>"},"sn1.59:0.3":{"pli":"Dutiyasutta ","eng":"A Partner ","html":"<h1 class='sutta-title'>{}</h1></header>"},"sn1.59:1.1":{"pli":"“Kiṃsu dutiyā purisassa hoti, ","eng":"“What is a person’s partner? ","html":"<blockquote class='gatha'><p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.59:1.2":{"pli":"Kiṃsu cenaṃ pasāsati; ","eng":"What instructs them? ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.59:1.3":{"pli":"Kissa cābhirato macco, ","eng":"Enjoying what is a mortal ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.59:1.4":{"pli":"Sabbadukkhā pamuccatī”ti. ","eng":"released from all suffering?” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.59:2.1":{"pli":"“Saddhā dutiyā purisassa hoti, ","eng":"“Faith is a person’s partner. ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.59:2.2":{"pli":"Paññā cenaṃ pasāsati; ","eng":"Wisdom instructs them. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.59:2.3":{"pli":"Nibbānābhirato macco, ","eng":"Delighting in extinguishment a mortal ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.59:2.4":{"pli":"Sabbadukkhā pamuccatī”ti. ","eng":"is released from all suffering.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p></blockquote></article>"}},"sn1.6":{"sn1.6:0.1":{"pli":"Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.6 ","eng":"Linked Discourses 1.6 ","html":"<article id='sn1.6'><header><ul><li class='division'>{}</li>"},"sn1.6:0.2":{"pli":"1. Naḷavagga ","eng":"1. A Reed ","html":"<li>{}</li></ul>"},"sn1.6:0.3":{"pli":"Jāgarasutta ","eng":"Awake ","html":"<h1 class='sutta-title'>{}</h1></header>"},"sn1.6:1.1":{"pli":"Sāvatthinidānaṃ. ","eng":"At Sāvatthī. ","html":"<p>{}</p>"},"sn1.6:1.2":{"pli":"Ekamantaṃ ṭhitā kho sā devatā bhagavato santike imaṃ gāthaṃ abhāsi: ","eng":"Standing to one side, that deity spoke this verse in the Buddha’s presence: ","html":"<p>{}</p>"},"sn1.6:2.1":{"pli":"“Kati jāgarataṃ suttā, ","eng":"“How many sleep among the waking? ","html":"<blockquote class='gatha'><p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.6:2.2":{"pli":"kati suttesu jāgarā; ","eng":"How many wake among the sleeping? ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.6:2.3":{"pli":"Katibhi rajamādeti, ","eng":"By how many do you gather dust? ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.6:2.4":{"pli":"katibhi parisujjhatī”ti. ","eng":"By how many are you cleansed?” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"sn1.6:3.1":{"pli":"“Pañca jāgarataṃ suttā, ","eng":"“Five sleep among the waking. ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"This verse is found in Isibhāsiyāiṁ 29.2, where it is attributed to the Jain Vardhamāna Mahāvīra. His explanation there takes the “five” as the senses, which for the “waking” sages are “asleep” (i.e. restrained), while the unawakened “sleep” in ignorance while their “awakened’ senses run riot. The Pali commentaries, on the other hand, take them as the five spiritual faculties on the side of awakening, in contrast with the five hindrances. "},"sn1.6:3.2":{"pli":"pañca suttesu jāgarā; ","eng":"Five wake among the sleeping. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.6:3.3":{"pli":"Pañcabhi rajamādeti, ","eng":"By five you gather dust. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"sn1.6:3.4":{"pli":"pañcabhi parisujjhatī”ti. ","eng":"By five you’re cleansed.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p></blockquote></article>"}}}